caption: Length at age in the beginning of the year (or season) in the ending year of the model. Shaded area indicates 95% distribution of length at age around estimated growth curve.
Length at age (top-left panel) with CV (thick line) and SD (thin line) of length at age shown in top-right and lower-left panels
Length at age (top-left panel) with weight (thick line) and maturity (thin line) shown in top-right and lower-left panels
Fecundity as a function of weight
Fecundity as a function of length
Spawning output at length. This is the product of maturity and fecundity unless maturity is age-based, in which case only fecundity is represented.
Spawning output at age. This is the product of maturity and fecundity. When these processes are length-based they are converted into the age dimension using the matrix of length at age.
Selectivity at length for multiple fleets.
Selectivity at age for multiple fleets.
Selectivity at age derived from selectivity at length for multiple fleets.

Summary biomass (t) at beginning of season 1
Summary F (definition of F depends on setting in starter.ss)

Dynamic B0 plot. The lower line shows the time series of estimated Spawning biomass (t) in the presence of fishing mortality. The upper line shows the time series that could occur under the same dynamics (including deviations in recruitment), but without fishing. The point at the left represents the unfished equilibrium.
Stock-recruit curve.  Point colors indicate year, with warmer colors indicating earlier years and cooler colors in showing later years.

Stock-recruit curve with labels on first, last, and years with (log) deviations > 0.5. Point colors indicate year, with warmer colors indicating earlier years and cooler colors in showing later years.

Deviations around the stock-recruit curve. Labels are on first, last, and years with (log) deviations > 0.5. Point colors indicate year, with warmer colors indicating earlier years and cooler colors in showing later years.

observed_and_expected_landings_(if_different). Catch input in numbers is compared here to catch in biomass, making this figure less useful for models like this with catch in numbers. Future versions of this plot will be improve to compare catch in the same units.
Timeseries of SPR. Horizontal line is at SPR at MSY: 0.27

Phase plot of biomass ratio vs. SPR ratio.
Each point represents the biomass ratio at the start of the year and the relative fishing intensity in that same year. Warmer colors (red) represent early years and colder colors (blue) represent recent years.

Index data for S01_INDEX.1-4. Lines indicate 95% uncertainty interval around index values based on the model assumption of lognormal error. Thicker lines (if present) indicate input uncertainty before addition of estimated additional uncertainty parameter.

Fit to index data for S01_INDEX.1-4. Lines indicate 95% uncertainty interval around index values based on the model assumption of lognormal error. Thicker lines (if present) indicate input uncertainty before addition of estimated additional uncertainty parameter.

Log index data for S01_INDEX.1-4. Lines indicate 95% uncertainty interval around index values based on the model assumption of lognormal error. Thicker lines (if present) indicate input uncertainty before addition of estimated additional uncertainty parameter.

Fit to log index data on log scale for S01_INDEX.1-4. Lines indicate 95% uncertainty interval around index values based on the model assumption of lognormal error. Thicker lines (if present) indicate input uncertainty before addition of estimated additional uncertainty parameter.
log(observed) vs. log(expected) index values with smoother for S01_INDEX.1-4

Residuals of fit to index for S01_INDEX.1-4.
Values are (log(Obs) - log(Exp))/SE where SE is the total standard error including any estimated additional uncertainty.

Deviations for fit to index for S01_INDEX.1-4.
Values are log(Obs) - log(Exp) and thus independent of index uncertainty.
Standardized indices overlaid. Each index is rescaled to have mean observation = 1.0.

Time series of yield per recruit (kg)
Data presence by year for each fleet and data type.

Data presence by year for each fleet, where circle area is
relative within a data type. Circles are proportional to
total catch for catches; to precision for indices, discards, and
mean body weight observations; and to total sample size for
compositions and mean weight- or length-at-age observations.
Observations excluded from the likelihood have
equal size for all years.
Note that since the circles are are scaled relative
to maximum within each type, the scaling within separate plots
should not be compared.
This is a seasonal model, so scaling is based on either
the sum of samples within each year (for things like comps)
or the average among observations within a year (for
things like index uncertainty).
